    {
      "id": "m6v43dav",
      "questionNumber": 4,
      "questionText": "<p>The hydrocarbon $(\\mathrm{X})$ with molar mass $80 \\mathrm{~g} \\mathrm{~mol}^{-1}$ and $90 \\%$ carbon has _______ degree of unsaturation.</p>",
      "options": [],
      "correctOption": 0,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "iupac-nomenclature",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>Mass of carbon $=\\frac{80 \\times 90}{100}=72 \\mathrm{gm}$</p>\n<p>Number of C-atoms $=\\frac{72}{12}=6$</p>\n<p>Mass of hydrogen $=\\frac{80 \\times 10}{800}=8 \\mathrm{gm}$</p>\n<p>Number of H -atoms $=\\frac{8}{1}=8$</p>\n<p>So molecular formula $\\mathrm{C}_6 \\mathrm{H}_8$</p>\n<p>D.U. $=6+1-8 / 2=7-4=3$</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
    {
      "id": "FltkfgWFfsS8fciFtw8HF",
      "questionNumber": 5,
      "questionText": "The correct match between items of <b>List-I</b> and <b>List-II</b> is :\n<br><br><style type=\"text/css\">\n.tg  {border-collapse:collapse;border-spacing:0;}\n.tg td{font-family:Arial, sans-serif;font-size:14px;padding:10px 5px;border-style:solid;border-width:1px;overflow:hidden;word-break:normal;border-color:black;}\n.tg th{font-family:Arial, sans-serif;font-size:14px;font-weight:normal;padding:10px 5px;border-style:solid;border-width:1px;overflow:hidden;word-break:normal;border-color:black;}\n.tg .tg-13k7{font-size:20px;text-align:left}\n.tg .tg-p7ly{font-weight:bold;font-size:20px;text-align:center}\n</style>\n<table class=\"tg\">\n  <tbody><tr>\n    <th class=\"tg-p7ly\" colspan=\"2\">List - I</th>\n    <th class=\"tg-p7ly\" colspan=\"2\">List - II</th>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-p7ly\">(A)</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-13k7\">Coloured impurity</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-p7ly\">(P)</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-13k7\">Steam distilation</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-p7ly\">(B)</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-13k7\">Mixture of o-nitrophenol <br>and p-nitrophenol</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-p7ly\">(Q)</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-13k7\">Fractional distilation</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-p7ly\">(C)</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-13k7\">Crude Naphtha </td>\n    <td class=\"tg-p7ly\">(R)</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-13k7\">Charcoal treatment</td>\n  </tr>\n  <tr>\n    <td class=\"tg-p7ly\">(d)</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-13k7\">Mixture of glycerol <br>and sugars</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-p7ly\">(S)</td>\n    <td class=\"tg-13k7\">Distillation under <br>reduced pressure</td>\n  </tr>\n</tbody></table>",
      "options": [
        "(A)-(R), (B)-(S), (C)-(P), (D)-(Q)",
        "(A)-(R), (B)-(P), (C)-(S), (D)-(Q)",
        "(A)-(R), (B)-(P), (C)-(Q), (D)-(S)",
        "(A)-(P), (B)-(S), (C)-(R), (D)-(Q)"
      ],
      "correctOption": 2,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "purification-of-organic-compounds",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "(a) Charcoal treatment removes coloured impurity through adsorption.\n<br><br>(b) Steam distillation separates the mixture of o-nitrophenol and p-nitrophenol. The o-nitrophenol is\nsteam volatile (due to intramolecular hydrogen bonding), and the para isomer is not volatile.\n<br><br>(c) Fractional distillation separates crude naphtha. Naphtha is a flammable liquid hydrocarbon\nmixture.\n<br><br>(d) Distillation under reduced pressure separates mixture of glycerol and sugars. Vacuum distillation\nlowers the boiling point and prevents decomposition.\n",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
    {
      "id": "1lgrlkiw3",
      "questionNumber": 6,
      "questionText": "<p>Three organic compounds A, B and $$\\mathrm{C}$$ were allowed to run in thin layer chromatography using hexane and gave the following result (see figure). The $$\\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$$ value of the most polar compound is ____________ $$\\times 10^{-2}$$</p>\n<p><img src=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/fly/@width/image/1lgse1t3w/ff3b72a6-f411-4adc-bd61-ee29a8334861/f84e7dc0-e145-11ed-a8e4-b7bc072b4abb/file-1lgse1t3x.png?format=png\" data-orsrc=\"https://app-content.cdn.examgoal.net/image/1lgse1t3w/ff3b72a6-f411-4adc-bd61-ee29a8334861/f84e7dc0-e145-11ed-a8e4-b7bc072b4abb/file-1lgse1t3x.png\" loading=\"lazy\" style=\"max-width:100%;height:auto;display:block;margin:0px auto;max-height:40vh\" alt=\"JEE Main 2023 (Online) 12th April Morning Shift Chemistry - Basics of Organic Chemistry Question 129 English\"></p>",
      "options": [],
      "correctOption": 0,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "purification-of-organic-compounds",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "In thin layer chromatography using hexane, the least polar compound will rise to maximum height and most polar compound will rise to minimum height.<br/><br/>\n$\\therefore \\mathrm{R}_{\\mathrm{f}}$ value for most polar compound<br/><br/>\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& =\\frac{2}{8}=0.25 \\\\\\\\\n& =25 \\times 10^{-2}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
    {
      "id": "mnt2t6wg",
      "questionNumber": 7,
      "questionText": "<p>Increasing order of electron withdrawing power of following functional groups is :</p>\n<p>a. -CN</p>\n<p>b. -COOH</p>\n<p>c. $-\\mathrm{NO}_2$</p>\n<p>d. -I</p>",
      "options": [
        "<p>$$ \\mathrm{c}<\\mathrm{b}<\\mathrm{d}<\\mathrm{a} $$</p>",
        "<p>$$ \\mathrm{c}<\\mathrm{a}<\\mathrm{b}<\\mathrm{d} $$</p>",
        "$$\n\\mathrm{d}<\\mathrm{b}<\\mathrm{a}<\\mathrm{c}\n$$",
        "<p>$$ \\mathrm{a}<\\mathrm{b}<\\mathrm{c}<\\mathrm{d} $$</p>"
      ],
      "correctOption": 2,
      "correctAnswer": null,
      "questionType": "MCQ",
      "marks": 4,
      "negativeMarks": -1,
      "subject": "Chemistry",
      "topic": "electron-displacement-effect",
      "difficulty": "Easy",
      "solution": "<p>To understand this question, we need to look at the Inductive effect, specifically the negative inductive effect ($-I$ effect), which determines the electron-withdrawing power of a functional group. </p>\n<p>According to the principles of organic chemistry laid out in your NCERT textbook, the electron-withdrawing nature of a group depends on the electronegativity of the atoms present in the group and their arrangement.</p>\n<p>The standard decreasing order of the $-I$ effect (electron-withdrawing power) for various functional groups is:</p>\n<p>$$ -\\mathrm{NO}_2 > -\\mathrm{CN} > -\\mathrm{COOH} > -\\mathrm{F} > -\\mathrm{Cl} > -\\mathrm{Br} > -\\mathrm{I} > -\\mathrm{OH} > -\\mathrm{OCH}_3 > -\\mathrm{C_6H_5} > -\\mathrm{H} $$</p>\n<p>Let us analyze the functional groups given in the question:</p>\n<ol>\n<li><p><strong>$ -\\mathrm{NO}_2 $ (c):</strong> This group has a nitrogen atom bonded to two highly electronegative oxygen atoms, and the nitrogen carries a formal positive charge. This makes it a very strong electron-withdrawing group.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>$ -\\mathrm{CN} $ (a):</strong> The carbon in the cyanide group is $sp$ hybridized, which makes it more electronegative. Coupled with the electronegative nitrogen atom, it exerts a strong $-I$ effect, but it is slightly weaker than $-\\mathrm{NO}_2$.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>$ -\\mathrm{COOH} $ (b):</strong> This group contains a carbonyl carbon attached to a hydroxyl oxygen. It shows a moderate $-I$ effect, which is weaker than both $-\\mathrm{NO}_2$ and $-\\mathrm{CN}$.</p></li>\n<li><p><strong>$ -\\mathrm{I} $ (d):</strong> Iodine is a halogen. While halogens are electronegative, iodine has the largest atomic size and the lowest electronegativity among the common halogens (fluorine, chlorine, bromine). Hence, it has the weakest $-I$ effect out of the groups listed here.</p></li>\n</ol>\n<p>Based on this analysis, the decreasing order of their electron-withdrawing power is:</p>\n<p>$$ \\mathrm{c} \\ (-\\mathrm{NO}_2) > \\mathrm{a} \\ (-\\mathrm{CN}) > \\mathrm{b} \\ (-\\mathrm{COOH}) > \\mathrm{d} \\ (-\\mathrm{I}) $$</p>\n<p>Therefore, rearranging them into the increasing order gives:</p>\n<p>$$ \\mathrm{d} < \\mathrm{b} < \\mathrm{a} < \\mathrm{c} $$</p>\n<p>This perfectly matches Option C.</p>\n<p><strong>Correct Answer:</strong></p>\n<p>Option C</p>\n<p>$$ \\mathrm{d} < \\mathrm{b} < \\mathrm{a} < \\mathrm{c} $$</p>",
      "section": "A",
      "instruction": "",
      "examSource": "jee-main"
    },
